std::exception and throw()

Base Class: std::exception is the base class for all standard exceptions in C++. 
It provides a virtual function called what() that returns a C-style string describing the exception.

Custom Exception: 
You can derive a custom exception class from std::exception if you want to provide more specific error messages 
	or handle specific types of errors. 
When you create an instance of your exception class, the constructor of your class is called, 
	followed by the constructor of std::exception.

Standard Exceptions: 
Alternatively, you can use existing exceptions like std::out_of_range or 
	std::invalid_argument if they fit your needs.

How throw Works:
-----------------------------
1) Throwing an Exception: 
	- When you use the throw keyword, you signal that an error has occurred. 
	- You create an instance of an exception (which can be an object of std::exception 
		or any derived class) and 
	- pass it to throw.

2) Exception Propagation: 
	- The throw keyword interrupts the normal flow of the program and starts unwinding the stack. 
	- The runtime looks for a matching catch block to handle the exception. 
	- If it finds one, the control is transferred to that block; 
	- otherwise, the program terminates.

3) Passing std::exception to throw():
	- you're providing an std::exception object that contains information about that error.
	- The throw keyword passes the exception object to the runtime system.
	-  runtime copies the exception object (using the copy constructor).
	- It stores this copy in a special location, typically referred to as the "exception object".
	- The runtime then initiates the stack unwinding process to search for a suitable catch block 
		that matches the type of the exception object.
	- When a matching catch block is found, the copied exception object is passed to it, 
		allowing the program to handle the error.
	
	- The throw keyword itself doesn’t perform complex operations;
	- it simply transfers control to the exception-handling mechanism, which takes over from there.

